üìåUnderstanding document, console, and window in JavaScript

üí†JavaScript interacts with web pages through three key objects:
  1Ô∏è‚É£document ‚Üí Used to manipulate the webpage content (DOM).
  2Ô∏è‚É£console ‚Üí Used for debugging and logging messages.
  3Ô∏è‚É£window ‚Üí Represents the browser window and provides global functions.


üìåExample Code Using document, console, and window
 _____________________________________________________________________________________________
|    <!DOCTYPE html>                                                                          |    
|    <html lang="en">                                                                         | 
|    <head>                                                                                   | 
|        <title>JavaScript Objects Example</title>                                            |
|    </head>                                                                                  |
|    <body>                                                                                   | 
|        <h1 id="title">Welcome to JavaScript!</h1>                                           | 
|        <button onclick="changeContent()">Change Content</button>                            |  
|        <button onclick="showAlert()">Show Alert</button>                                    |
|                                                                                             | 
|        <script>                                                                             | 
|            // Using document: Manipulating the webpage (DOM)                                |
|            function changeContent() {                                                       |   
|                document.getElementById("title").innerText = "JavaScript is awesome!";       | 
|                console.log("Title changed successfully!"); // Using console for debugging   | 
|            }                                                                                |      
|                                                                                             | 
|            // Using window: Interacting with the browser                                    |  
|            function showAlert() {                                                           | 
|                window.alert("This is a window alert!");                                     | 
|                console.log("Alert displayed!"); // Using console to track actions           |
|            }                                                                                |
|                                                                                             | 
|            // Using console: Debugging information                                          |
|            console.log("Page Loaded! Ready to execute JavaScript.");                        |
|        </script>                                                                            |
|    </body>                                                                                  |
|    </html>                                                                                  |
|_____________________________________________________________________________________________|


üìåExplanation:

1Ô∏è‚É£document (DOM Manipulation)  (acces to html)
  üí†document.getElementById("title").innerText = "JavaScript is awesome!";
  üí†Modifies the content of an HTML element dynamically.

2Ô∏è‚É£console (Debugging & Logging)
  üí†console.log("Title changed successfully!");
  üí†Prints messages to the browser console, useful for debugging.

3Ô∏è‚É£window (Global Browser Object)
  üí†window.alert("This is a window alert!");
  üí†Triggers a browser pop-up alert.


üìåWhy Use These?
Feature	Purpose
document	To modify the webpage dynamically (change text, styles, etc.).
console	To debug JavaScript code by logging messages.
window	To interact with the browser (alerts, navigation, timers, etc.).
